{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FQmBeVLhYQFWHYkxV1kWEU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The TLS cert for ES is only for internal cluster names, not for `es.example.com`. I need to create a new TLS certificate for `es.example.com` and use it in the Ingress.\n\nKey observations:\n1. The `es-http` service is on port 9200 and Elasticsearch is running with HTTPS (the service port is named \"https\")\n2. I need to create an Ingress that:\n   - Terminates TLS at nginx with a cert for `es.example.com`\n   - Passes traffic to `es-http` on port 9200\n   - Since ES uses HTTPS internally, I need the nginx to talk to the backend via HTTPS (passthrough or SSL proxy)\n   - Redirects HTTP to HTTPS\n\nI have two approaches: SSL passthrough where nginx forwards the TLS connection directly to ES, or TLS termination at nginx with HTTPS proxying to the backend. For the latter, I'll use the `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/backend-protocol: \"HTTPS\"` annotation to tell nginx to communicate with the ES backend over HTTPS.\n\nSince the existing `es-http-tls` secret only has certs for internal names, I need to generate a self-signed certificate for `es.example.com`, create a Kubernetes TLS secret from it, and then set up an Ingress resource with the nginx ingress class. I can also add an annotation to block plain HTTP traffic.\n\nFor the backend connection, I should set the backend protocol to HTTPS since Elasticsearch uses TLS internally. Let me check if openssl is available to generate the certificate.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1667,"cache_read_input_tokens":30188,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1667},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_i